Scottish independent schools enjoy a reputation for academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding results on exams, further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, the chosen career path and the place they have as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, the conversation will impress him in his memory.
But if you speak to a man in his mother tongue, words are imprinted on his heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results of recent exams show that languages are at the top of the scale with the highest levels of achievement in independent schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who learned a foreign language achieved an excellent grade.
Data collected in 74 member schools of the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) showed that 72% of pupils achieved an excellent score in Mandarin, while 72% of German pupils, 69% of French pupils and 63% of French pupils also received an excellent score.
