Red Wave News: Coastal concentrations of Pinellas, Manatee and Saratosa are declining
A recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC) shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
The FWC commission reported more widespread flowering in the Pinellas, Manatee, Saratosa, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide stretches about 130 miles from the northern coast of Pinellas County to the southern districts of Lee County.
Paid is seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and along its coast, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, basic to high concentrations in Manatee County, basic to high concentrations in Saratosa County and along its coast, basic to high concentrations in Le County and high concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation from Northwest Florida in the past week.
